subtitle: Sarah Arao Mantle of Hope- Thank You Video to the Y on Earth Community for GoFundMe Campaign Support
description: Well, let me just remind our audience that this is the YonEarth Communities Stewardship and Sustainability Podcasts series.
full_transcript:
[7.7s - 13.4s]: Welcome to the Y on Earth communities stewardship and sustainability podcast series.

[14.1s - 20.0s]: Today we are visiting with Dehoon Jiosta, also known as Meadow Cook.

[21.0s - 22.1s]: Hey Meadow, how are you doing?

[22.5s - 22.7s]: I'm good.

[23.1s - 24.3s]: It's good to be with you.

[24.5s - 25.1s]: Yeah, you too.

[26.1s - 40.2s]: And I'm so excited to dive into this conversation about all of this leadership work that you're doing as a youth ambassador, as a youth advisory board member on a handful of different organizations.

[41.2s - 48.5s]: And can't wait to talk with you about the project that you're doing right here on these lands where we're currently sitting.

[48.5s - 55.5s]: And before we dive in, let me share with the audience a little bit about you in your background.

[56.9s - 64.8s]: So Dehoon Jiosta, Meadow Cook, is a 16 year old indigenous activist from the Aquasasni Mohawk territory.

[65.4s - 69.5s]: She is Bear clan and an environmentalist within her community.

[70.5s - 78.3s]: She has been actively involved with the Idle No More movement and is currently involved in the fight against the Enbridge pipeline.

[79.6s - 93.1s]: Meadow is an indigenous representative for Earth uprising, is president of the Three Sisters Sovereignty Project Youth Advisory Board, and is an ambassador of the Y on Earth community.

[93.7s - 103.7s]: She hopes to expand her reach beyond the reserve and act for a voice for the Ganyak Kihaga, the Mohawk people.

[104.8s - 112.6s]: So Meadow, this is a lot. You've got a lot going on and I'm so impressed that you're doing so much at the age of 16.

[113.6s - 122.7s]: And there's a lot we're going to be able to share at the audience here. So to dive in, will you share where are we right now and why is that important?

[123.4s - 133.8s]: So right now we're in the Scoheri Valley. It's actually the ancestral lands of the Mohawk people. And we just moved back here, Me and my mom.

[134.8s - 139.4s]: And we're working with the Three Sisters Project to help reclaim this land back.

[141.2s - 149.5s]: And so how does it feel for you having recently moved here to this land versus where you've grown up?

[150.4s - 158.5s]: It feels like it's like a connection that I've never really felt at home on a reservation.

[158.5s - 170.9s]: And to be here surrounded by the nature and in a place that isn't toxic and killing our people is a really different feeling.

[171.4s - 173.8s]: Like even just going home.

[177.0s - 184.2s]: We get like these headaches and we get sick for a couple days, the first few days that we're back every time we return.

[185.0s - 190.5s]: And as soon as we come back here, we're better and it takes a couple days to adjust.

[191.8s - 194.4s]: And that just shows how toxic it is at home.

[195.4s - 201.9s]: Yeah. And I imagine a lot of our audience doesn't know where aquasawsini is in terms of the geography of it all.

[202.0s - 208.4s]: Could you just kind of describe what where it is and then why we're talking about this environmental pollution?

[208.4s - 215.7s]: Yeah, so I'm from upstate New York. It straddles the border of Canada and New York.

[216.2s - 226.7s]: So part of our reservation is in Ontario and part is in the like, Masina area. It's a small town.

[226.9s - 228.9s]: It's like the way northern Adirondex basically.

[229.4s - 229.4s]: 

[230.4s - 240.6s]: And we actually live on a super fun site and there's two main factories that were shut down.

[241.3s - 252.2s]: But they were never really taken care properly. So now all of our people are getting sick and basically dying off in a new way and a new genocide because of this.

[253.2s - 259.9s]: And this is something obviously that you've got lots of your friends and family dealing with directly.

[260.5s - 267.1s]: And we know through many of our other ambassadors and friends and allies at the Y-Earth community,

[267.1s - 275.6s]: this kind of environmental justice issue is one that we're seeing in a lot of different places around the United States, around North America and even globally.

[275.6s - 302.3s]: And it's really important, I think, that we all have a much higher level of awareness about what's going on here and that we have these manufacturing facilities often discharging any meeting horrible carcinogens, heavy metals into the environment often around places like reservations and other disempowered or low income communities that might be found around major cities, etc.

[303.3s - 310.7s]: So what's happening from your perspective as a youth leader to help deal with that challenging situation?

[313.3s - 331.0s]: So at home it's really hard to go back because all of the youth there and even myself for the majority of my life, we felt this sense of hopelessness and like this is just what happens to us.

[331.0s - 350.6s]: And even just doing research if you look at the number one, like the top 10 superfund sites in New York, like half of them are all reservations and they're all within the Hunanashani community.

[353.3s - 371.9s]: So it's really hard. Even other reservations near us going visit, you see all the pollution that it's caused, all the disease that it's caused us and no one's really, I don't really even know that home even.

[371.9s - 381.4s]: And that's how, like, kind of covered up and hidden it was in operation.

[382.3s - 391.9s]: And these are often manufacturing facilities from companies we would all be familiar with, right? Like I think is it general motors and Alcoa?

[391.9s - 396.0s]: Yeah, major aluminum manufacturer among other things, right?

[396.4s - 416.5s]: Yeah. And of course so many of us are using the products coming from these companies and it's imperative we connect the dots in terms of our consumer demand and really demanding that we see these companies taking responsibility for things they've already done and stop that kind of behavior going forward.

[417.5s - 437.3s]: Yeah. The worst is the people who have worked in the plants. So they not only lost their jobs when they shut down, they're losing their lives because of the disease and everything that's spread to them, working in those factories in close proximity to all these chemicals and toxins.

[437.3s - 461.0s]: Yeah. That's really intense. Well, I am so struck that notwithstanding these incredible challenges, you have grown up with such a strong sense of self. And as such a strong leader, right? You've been class president more than one year.

[461.0s - 473.4s]: Yeah. And maybe tell us a little bit about that. Like what's that like in terms of being a leader in your role as class president? Like how does that feel to you?

[474.4s - 501.9s]: Well, it was really different being that kind of leader in a school where it was the majority native students, but none of them are interested in leading and that always really confused me because I always knew I wanted to do something to help the people and even like my classmates even just get better conditions in school.

[501.9s - 527.5s]: And it was really, I knew it was what I wanted to do as soon as the option was available. So I started in fifth grade and I was president four years straight, co-president one year. And then I was the student rep the fifth year.

[529.2s - 538.7s]: And I've tried the majority of the student council was always non native, but the majority of the school is native.

[538.9s - 541.5s]: Like what 80, 85% or something? Yeah, 85%.

[542.4s - 553.2s]: And so I would always feel like I was presenting these ideas and the non native students would just brush it off kind of.

[553.2s - 569.5s]: So it's hard to almost like the way that they are at home is hard to work with them and get them to recognize the things that our people are going through even though they live in such close proximity. They don't understand.

[570.3s - 579.0s]: So if I tried my best, but it's hard to work with our school board pretty much.

[579.0s - 591.9s]: Yeah, big challenge. Well, and now that you've moved to central New York, obviously there's a whole new opportunity in the way that you're leading with your peers back in aquasawks.

[591.9s - 604.4s]: And I know just the last couple nights we've been here at a gathering for several days and it's been so fun observing you communicating with your friends back in aquasawks.

[604.4s - 610.8s]: And I'm actually telling them about what's going on here and the level of excitement is palpable. It's amazing, right?

[611.1s - 618.6s]: So what are some of your friends thinking about in terms of what's happening at three sister sovereignty project and how they might get involved?

[623.1s - 629.1s]: So more than half of the people that I've had, I've put together youth forward.

[629.1s - 644.6s]: So more than half of them are fluent in the language and they're going to bring that aspect because a lot of the older people and even a bigger majority of the younger people have lost our language.

[645.1s - 650.8s]: So it was really important to make sure that we could have that aspect in this.

[650.8s - 662.7s]: And so I have multiple language speakers on the board and I have multiple traditional artists.

[663.7s - 673.7s]: We have basket weavers, painters, sketch artists, and beaters, a big part.

[674.7s - 688.2s]: So I wanted every aspect of our culture to be able to include the youth and really bring connect that with the older women working with the three sister sovereignty project.

[689.2s - 691.5s]: That's so exciting. Are they excited to get down there?

[691.5s - 702.6s]: Yeah. I feel like I've given them a sense of hope that they didn't know that they had, that they could have or like an option that they didn't think was available.

[703.3s - 710.9s]: And a lot of them were so excited and felt like they had a purpose for the first time.

[712.8s - 738.9s]: So they really, all of them are on board instantly and their parents are also super supportive because they know how important this work is and how important the revival of our culture is after not being able to, like the older generation, not being able to even participate in their own culture up until was it the 70s?

[738.9s - 745.5s]: Yeah. So it's a lot of them were working to heal that intergenerational trauma.

[745.8s - 755.4s]: Yeah. It's absolutely admirable. And the courage and the power that you're demonstrating just naturally is really beautiful.

[755.9s - 763.2s]: I commend you for that and I'm so happy we have the opportunity to share that a bit with our audience. It's tremendous.

[763.2s - 776.6s]: And I know that some of our audience is familiar with some of the brutality and the oppression and what's happened as the European forces have colonized around the world, including right here.

[777.2s - 788.6s]: And what I don't think everybody necessarily has a direct experience of or a direct knowledge of is the stories of what happens when we're little kids and we're not allowed to speak our native language.

[788.6s - 802.5s]: And there are people teaching us not related to us who are using brutal methods to basically indoctrinated and cultureate us into mainstream white English culture.

[803.3s - 809.8s]: And this is part of what you're talking about healing that intergenerational wounding that's been there for many generations now.

[809.8s - 827.5s]: Yeah. So there's like in my own family alone, there's at least five generations of trauma. And even my own mother wasn't allowed to speak her language.

[827.5s - 846.1s]: So it's really important to be doing that work and bringing it back. And I think with this project, even including more youth is just going to further the healing and connect all of them.

[846.1s - 857.9s]: Yeah. And of course, your mother is one of the three women leading the three sisters sovereignty project, right? So this is just a tremendous story.

[859.0s - 864.7s]: And it's one I hope many of our why on earth network will get involved in and engaged in and support.

[865.4s - 887.7s]: And I'll just throw out that you can check out information on three sisters by going to three sisters project.org. And there is a go fund me underway to help support the efforts in the coming year of putting in gardens, of putting in an educational long house, of getting some sustainable micro enterprises launched in underway.

[887.7s - 902.3s]: So three sisters project.org is a great place to plug in and to support what's happening here with meadow and her mother Tiffany and the other women and men who are helping to make this happen.

[903.3s - 908.8s]: So yeah, definitely excited for folks to have an opportunity to see that and to become a part of that.

[909.7s - 923.2s]: And of course, I some folks know that my great grandmother was Mohawk and that that you know, I'm one of the people out there who's got that as part of my heritage, but was totally obviously cut off culturally.

[923.8s - 936.7s]: And for me, I get excited thinking I have an opportunity to learn the language a little bit. And it's not easy. It's a beautiful language. I love hearing it. And it's not an easy one for me to learn.

[937.0s - 948.6s]: But Dehunjio's, your name has a beautiful, beautiful meaning. Can you can you share with the audience what it means and what it means to you as you're moving here and doing this work here?

[948.6s - 967.4s]: So my name, Dehunjio's stuff means she makes the line beautiful. And I was named by my grandmother. It's really kind of astonishing to see how it's manifested and how it's really become my true name.

[967.9s - 975.2s]: And I just feeling the connection to the land here has only furthered that.

[977.8s - 993.0s]: And you with with your mother and several other women had an amazing ceremony a few days ago, moon lodge ceremony. And I understand that was for you the first lodge ceremony you've had back here on the ancestral homelands. Is that right?

[993.0s - 1015.5s]: Yeah, so our first our moon ceremony was for all the women. And it was mainly to connect us back to this land because we've been gone for so long. And because we were pushed to our reservations and we haven't been here. And we all really felt that connection while we were in there doing the ceremony.

[1017.2s - 1041.1s]: That's absolutely beautiful. Well, I think another aspect of what's happening that's really important for all of our audience and really all of our society to understand where broadly is that coming out of the Mohawk tradition is a very powerful important special way of relating to each other and relating to the world, the earth. And it's the great law.

[1041.1s - 1051.0s]: And I know that Ben Franklin spent a lot of time among the Mohawk people and that was a big part of some of the most virtuous aspects of what got framed in the Constitution.

[1051.4s - 1058.8s]: And I'm just wondering share with us the great law and how does that play out in what you're doing here.

[1058.8s - 1072.8s]: So it's really hard for us to even follow the great law at home because the pollution has like poisoned our minds and all you can ever be is negative.

[1072.8s - 1097.5s]: And one of the main things we need to have is going to go near and that's a good mind. So coming here has really helped us reconnect with those teachings and really continuing to use it and show our youth how to use it because everyone is just disconnected mainly at home.

[1098.3s - 1103.5s]: And I know the great law has three main tenets, right? We share what those are.

[1106.8s - 1110.0s]: Peace. This is a good mind.

[1111.4s - 1112.1s]: And love.

[1118.1s - 1119.8s]: We've got mom off camera. Yeah.

[1119.8s - 1120.4s]: Yeah.

[1121.9s - 1124.4s]: It's been a while since I've studied that.

[1125.4s - 1135.2s]: So we learn, we basically learn that when we're little children and a lot of because there's no reservation schools other than the freedom school.

[1135.5s - 1137.7s]: And that's in one of the most polluted places.

[1138.1s - 1138.6s]: Oh my gosh.

[1138.8s - 1145.7s]: Our only option is to go to the white school. I mean it's still the majority of us have to go there.

[1145.7s - 1147.9s]: So it's now it's 85%.

[1147.9s - 1160.4s]: So once we, after we're children, if we're not able to go to long house because we can't miss school or the school gives us a hard time for ceremonies.

[1161.3s - 1172.0s]: So after we've all like forgotten basically and it's really hard to relearn things that you knew since you were baby.

[1172.5s - 1172.8s]: Yeah.

[1172.8s - 1174.6s]: That's mainly what we're all doing.

[1175.1s - 1176.6s]: Yeah. It's so beautiful to see you.

[1176.8s - 1182.5s]: And just earlier today, you were doing a bit of this nearby, right?

[1182.8s - 1188.5s]: There's an Irkoy Indian Museum nearby near house cave in Central New York.

[1189.4s - 1192.9s]: And you were over there teaching how many kids were over there?

[1193.2s - 1195.1s]: There was 70.

[1195.6s - 1195.8s]: Yeah.

[1195.9s - 1196.5s]: About 70.

[1196.5s - 1204.1s]: And so we were visiting yesterday that some of the artifacts are just beautiful to look at, right?

[1204.3s - 1206.5s]: And just amazing to be surrounded by all of that.

[1207.1s - 1210.2s]: What were you teaching the kids today? What was going on?

[1210.4s - 1217.5s]: So I was telling this big group about the story of the Cornhouse-style, the No Face-Daw.

[1217.9s - 1218.0s]: Yeah.

[1218.4s - 1221.8s]: And then we helped them to all make them.

[1221.8s - 1227.5s]: And it was so crazy to see all these non-native kids be so accepting.

[1228.2s - 1235.8s]: And they were all amazed that I was there because a lot of people think that the mohaks have died out.

[1236.1s - 1236.3s]: Right.

[1236.5s - 1242.7s]: And even just all Native Americans, they were all like, I thought they all died.

[1243.2s - 1244.9s]: And it was kind of crazy to see that.

[1245.2s - 1250.9s]: And I was speaking to them in the language and they were all so excited and thrilled to be there.

[1250.9s - 1252.3s]: So it was a really good experience.

[1252.8s - 1253.9s]: That's absolutely beautiful.

[1254.1s - 1255.0s]: That's so beautiful.

[1255.2s - 1259.8s]: Yeah. And it sounds like there will be opportunities for a lot more events and gatherings at that museum.

[1259.8s - 1261.2s]: It's a beautiful building, right?

[1261.5s - 1261.6s]: Yeah.

[1262.0s - 1264.3s]: So they want me to volunteer there now.

[1264.7s - 1268.1s]: So I'm going to be there often, me and my mom.

[1268.4s - 1275.1s]: And they want me to do some of the stories and tell them to the groups of kids for school.

[1275.5s - 1278.8s]: So they can learn and know that we're still here.

[1278.8s - 1280.2s]: Yeah, absolutely.

[1280.6s - 1281.4s]: And how.

[1282.4s - 1283.0s]: Yeah.

[1284.2s - 1288.3s]: Well, let's talk a little about sports for a minute.

[1289.0s - 1291.5s]: You also are a lacrosse player, huh?

[1291.8s - 1291.9s]: Yeah.

[1292.4s - 1293.5s]: Retired lacrosse player.

[1293.5s - 1294.9s]: Retired lacrosse player, yeah.

[1295.2s - 1301.4s]: So tell us lacrosse has a very special place in the mohak culture.

[1302.8s - 1304.4s]: Why is that special?

[1304.5s - 1305.0s]: What's that all about?

[1305.2s - 1308.0s]: And what changed recently with the clan mothers around?

[1308.0s - 1310.8s]: Um, so it's originally a medicine game.

[1311.0s - 1312.1s]: It was played by the men.

[1312.9s - 1321.9s]: And we used wooden sticks and it was made like, so like, we don't even have record because it's all oral storytelling.

[1322.9s - 1326.7s]: And, um, so the I grew up on.

[1327.5s - 1331.4s]: It wasn't my mom that ever wanted me to play because the women aren't supposed to play.

[1331.5s - 1333.1s]: We're in our culture.

[1333.1s - 1334.0s]: We're too powerful.

[1334.0s - 1339.3s]: And we're too, um, yeah, like we have too much power over it.

[1339.4s - 1340.8s]: So we can't use it as the medicine.

[1341.8s - 1349.9s]: So, um, my father was the one who got me into playing when I was in third grade.

[1350.8s - 1355.7s]: And even then it was a really controversial thing in our community.

[1356.3s - 1362.0s]: And a lot of people from the long house and the clan mothers and the leaders didn't support it.

[1362.0s - 1369.0s]: So in the last couple of years we've gotten, um, the Bear Clan Mother Louise Herndt.

[1369.9s - 1372.0s]: We got her on board with that.

[1372.4s - 1375.6s]: And we actually have a documentary about the whole process.

[1376.2s - 1379.2s]: It's called Keepers of the Game on Netflix.

[1381.6s - 1384.0s]: Yeah, I, uh, I watch it not well.

[1384.0s - 1387.7s]: I guess one or two years ago and it was awesome, awesome story.

[1388.0s - 1388.6s]: Keepers of the Game.

[1388.6s - 1396.8s]: Um, I'll put that in the show notes to, uh, I'll try to link it for everybody so that it's easy to check that out.

[1398.8s - 1403.5s]: So, uh, do you think you'll end up teaching some others to play some lacrosse down the road?

[1404.2s - 1405.0s]: Yeah, probably.

[1405.4s - 1413.6s]: Um, I mean, we have, uh, I have, uh, on my youth board for three sister sovereignty project.

[1413.6s - 1423.0s]: Um, we have a lot of lacrosse players and they, um, they know how to do the traditional wooden sticks and how to do everything involved with that.

[1423.6s - 1432.5s]: So, um, usually we split so the young men teach the young women and the young women teach the young women.

[1432.9s - 1441.1s]: Yeah, because it is different because, um, we use it more, the women use it more as a sport now.

[1441.1s - 1447.2s]: And it's not really the medicine aspect, but the young men still use that.

[1449.2s - 1454.9s]: So, um, there's more of a spiritual aspect to that too.

[1455.5s - 1463.3s]: And a lot of, like, probably the majority of young men on the reservation play and they've played their whole lives.

[1463.3s - 1465.0s]: Hmm, cool.

[1466.3s - 1475.2s]: I'm wondering too if we might share a little about, uh, the ego feather and, uh, another something very special hanging behind it here.

[1475.7s - 1475.9s]: Yeah.

[1476.2s - 1485.3s]: Uh, this is something from a man who's done a lot to reestablish the presence of the Mohawk people in this region as well, right?

[1485.6s - 1485.9s]: Yeah.

[1485.9s - 1492.9s]: And, uh, could you tell us a little about him and what this is and we'll, we can read it maybe for the audience, right?

[1493.1s - 1499.1s]: Yeah. Um, so Tom Porter, he, well, he's kind of a celebrity back home.

[1500.0s - 1506.9s]: Um, he's really done a lot of work for us in our community and really helped to establish another community,

[1507.5s - 1510.4s]: almost like our three sisters sovereignty project.

[1511.1s - 1517.6s]: So, he was kind of the, um, paved the way for us to even be here and be started.

[1518.4s - 1525.6s]: And, um, he's done a lot of work, a lot of speeches, a lot of top telling our stories and getting the message out there.

[1526.0s - 1530.7s]: There's a lot on YouTube, we used to watch it for our classes even in school.

[1531.4s - 1534.1s]: Like, that's how important it was to us to get that.

[1534.9s - 1535.9s]: That's so beautiful.

[1536.2s - 1538.9s]: Cool. Well, you know what I'm going to do, a little fun thing for our audience.

[1538.9s - 1543.3s]: I'm actually going to grab the camera and just kind of come in a little closer as you're reading it,

[1543.4s - 1548.7s]: just so we keep the sound as good as we can and maybe folks will be able to see what's going on.

[1548.8s - 1551.0s]: So this poster you just got at the museum, right?

[1551.3s - 1556.4s]: Yeah, actually my, um, my aunt does the artwork for this.

[1558.2s - 1560.4s]: So, this is the story of the Eagle Feather.

[1561.1s - 1564.6s]: When the world was new, the creator made all the birds.

[1565.1s - 1567.6s]: He colored their feathers like a bouquet of flowers.

[1568.3s - 1571.2s]: The creator then gave each a distinct song to sing.

[1571.8s - 1576.1s]: The creator instructed the birds to greet each new day with a chorus of their songs.

[1576.8s - 1580.0s]: Of all the birds, our creator chose the eagle to be the leader.

[1580.6s - 1583.9s]: The eagle flies the highest and sees the furthest of all creatures.

[1584.6s - 1586.8s]: The eagle is a messenger to the creator.

[1586.8s - 1591.2s]: During the four sacred rituals, we will wear an eagle feather in our hair.

[1592.0s - 1596.8s]: To wear or to hold the eagle feather causes our creator to take immediate notice.

[1597.2s - 1599.8s]: With the eagle feather, the creator is honored in the highest.

[1600.8s - 1604.8s]: When one receives an eagle feather, that person is being acknowledged with gratitude,

[1605.4s - 1607.3s]: with love and with ultimate respect.

[1608.0s - 1611.0s]: The feather must have sacred tobacco burnt for it.

[1611.0s - 1616.3s]: In this way, the eagle and the creator are notified of the name of the new eagle feather holder.

[1616.7s - 1622.9s]: The holder of the eagle feather must ensure that anything that changes the natural state of one's mind,

[1623.4s - 1628.7s]: like alcohol or drugs, it must never come in contact with the sacred eagle feather.

[1629.1s - 1632.3s]: The keeper of the feather will make a little home where the feather will be kept.

[1633.1s - 1636.9s]: The eagle feather must be fed, must, you feed the eagle feather.

[1636.9s - 1640.8s]: By holding or wearing the feather as their sacred ceremonies.

[1641.2s - 1644.6s]: By doing this, the eagle feathers recharged with sacred energy.

[1645.3s - 1649.5s]: Never abused, never disrespect, and never contaminate your eagle feather.

[1650.1s - 1653.4s]: Only real human men and women carry the eagle feather.

[1653.7s - 1658.1s]: The mohawk man will have three eagle feathers standing straight up on his gistowa.

[1658.8s - 1661.1s]: This is what I know about the sacred eagle feather.

[1666.0s - 1667.7s]: Thank you.

[1679.3s - 1685.4s]: The clan mothers often give eagle feathers don't they for good deeds?

[1688.1s - 1692.0s]: Sometimes you don't even need my mom as hers.

[1692.5s - 1699.1s]: She got that on her own and did her own ceremony for it.

[1700.3s - 1702.9s]: She's starting to pass her things down to me.

segments.text: Welcome to the Y on Earth communities stewardship and sustainability podcast series.
Today we are visiting with Dehoon Jiosta, also known as Meadow Cook.
Hey Meadow, how are you doing?
I'm good.
It's good to be with you.
Yeah, you too.
And I'm so excited to dive into this conversation about all of this leadership work that you're doing as a youth ambassador, as a youth advisory board member on a handful of different organizations.
And can't wait to talk with you about the project that you're doing right here on these lands where we're currently sitting.
And before we dive in, let me share with the audience a little bit about you in your background.
So Dehoon Jiosta, Meadow Cook, is a 16 year old indigenous activist from the Aquasasni Mohawk territory.
She is Bear clan and an environmentalist within her community.
She has been actively involved with the Idle No More movement and is currently involved in the fight against the Enbridge pipeline.
Meadow is an indigenous representative for Earth uprising, is president of the Three Sisters Sovereignty Project Youth Advisory Board, and is an ambassador of the Y on Earth community.
She hopes to expand her reach beyond the reserve and act for a voice for the Ganyak Kihaga, the Mohawk people.
So Meadow, this is a lot. You've got a lot going on and I'm so impressed that you're doing so much at the age of 16.
And there's a lot we're going to be able to share at the audience here. So to dive in, will you share where are we right now and why is that important?
So right now we're in the Scoheri Valley. It's actually the ancestral lands of the Mohawk people. And we just moved back here, Me and my mom.
And we're working with the Three Sisters Project to help reclaim this land back.
And so how does it feel for you having recently moved here to this land versus where you've grown up?
It feels like it's like a connection that I've never really felt at home on a reservation.
And to be here surrounded by the nature and in a place that isn't toxic and killing our people is a really different feeling.
Like even just going home.
We get like these headaches and we get sick for a couple days, the first few days that we're back every time we return.
And as soon as we come back here, we're better and it takes a couple days to adjust.
And that just shows how toxic it is at home.
Yeah. And I imagine a lot of our audience doesn't know where aquasawsini is in terms of the geography of it all.
Could you just kind of describe what where it is and then why we're talking about this environmental pollution?
Yeah, so I'm from upstate New York. It straddles the border of Canada and New York.
So part of our reservation is in Ontario and part is in the like, Masina area. It's a small town.
It's like the way northern Adirondex basically.
And we actually live on a super fun site and there's two main factories that were shut down.
But they were never really taken care properly. So now all of our people are getting sick and basically dying off in a new way and a new genocide because of this.
And this is something obviously that you've got lots of your friends and family dealing with directly.
And we know through many of our other ambassadors and friends and allies at the Y-Earth community,
this kind of environmental justice issue is one that we're seeing in a lot of different places around the United States, around North America and even globally.

And it's really important, I think, that we all have a much higher level of awareness about what's going on here and that we have these manufacturing facilities often discharging any meeting horrible carcinogens, heavy metals into the environment often around places like reservations and other disempowered or low income communities that might be found around major cities, etc.
So what's happening from your perspective as a youth leader to help deal with that challenging situation?
So at home it's really hard to go back because all of the youth there and even myself for the majority of my life, we felt this sense of hopelessness and like this is just what happens to us.
And even just doing research if you look at the number one, like the top 10 superfund sites in New York, like half of them are all reservations and they're all within the Hunanashani community.

So it's really hard. Even other reservations near us going visit, you see all the pollution that it's caused, all the disease that it's caused us and no one's really, I don't really even know that home even.
And that's how, like, kind of covered up and hidden it was in operation.
And these are often manufacturing facilities from companies we would all be familiar with, right? Like I think is it general motors and Alcoa?
Yeah, major aluminum manufacturer among other things, right?

Yeah. And of course so many of us are using the products coming from these companies and it's imperative we connect the dots in terms of our consumer demand and really demanding that we see these companies taking responsibility for things they've already done and stop that kind of behavior going forward.

Yeah. The worst is the people who have worked in the plants. So they not only lost their jobs when they shut down, they're losing their lives because of the disease and everything that's spread to them, working in those factories in close proximity to all these chemicals and toxins.

Yeah. That's really intense. Well, I am so struck that notwithstanding these incredible challenges, you have grown up with such a strong sense of self. And as such a strong leader, right? You've been class president more than one year.
Yeah. And maybe tell us a little bit about that. Like what's that like in terms of being a leader in your role as class president? Like how does that feel to you?

Well, it was really different being that kind of leader in a school where it was the majority native students, but none of them are interested in leading and that always really confused me because I always knew I wanted to do something to help the people and even like my classmates even just get better conditions in school.

And it was really, I knew it was what I wanted to do as soon as the option was available. So I started in fifth grade and I was president four years straight, co-president one year. And then I was the student rep the fifth year.
And I've tried the majority of the student council was always non native, but the majority of the school is native.
Like what 80, 85% or something? Yeah, 85%.
And so I would always feel like I was presenting these ideas and the non native students would just brush it off kind of.

So it's hard to almost like the way that they are at home is hard to work with them and get them to recognize the things that our people are going through even though they live in such close proximity. They don't understand.
So if I tried my best, but it's hard to work with our school board pretty much.
Yeah, big challenge. Well, and now that you've moved to central New York, obviously there's a whole new opportunity in the way that you're leading with your peers back in aquasawks.
And I know just the last couple nights we've been here at a gathering for several days and it's been so fun observing you communicating with your friends back in aquasawks.
And I'm actually telling them about what's going on here and the level of excitement is palpable. It's amazing, right?
So what are some of your friends thinking about in terms of what's happening at three sister sovereignty project and how they might get involved?
So more than half of the people that I've had, I've put together youth forward.
So more than half of them are fluent in the language and they're going to bring that aspect because a lot of the older people and even a bigger majority of the younger people have lost our language.
So it was really important to make sure that we could have that aspect in this.
And so I have multiple language speakers on the board and I have multiple traditional artists.
We have basket weavers, painters, sketch artists, and beaters, a big part.
So I wanted every aspect of our culture to be able to include the youth and really bring connect that with the older women working with the three sister sovereignty project.
That's so exciting. Are they excited to get down there?
Yeah. I feel like I've given them a sense of hope that they didn't know that they had, that they could have or like an option that they didn't think was available.
And a lot of them were so excited and felt like they had a purpose for the first time.

So they really, all of them are on board instantly and their parents are also super supportive because they know how important this work is and how important the revival of our culture is after not being able to, like the older generation, not being able to even participate in their own culture up until was it the 70s?
Yeah. So it's a lot of them were working to heal that intergenerational trauma.
Yeah. It's absolutely admirable. And the courage and the power that you're demonstrating just naturally is really beautiful.
I commend you for that and I'm so happy we have the opportunity to share that a bit with our audience. It's tremendous.
And I know that some of our audience is familiar with some of the brutality and the oppression and what's happened as the European forces have colonized around the world, including right here.

And what I don't think everybody necessarily has a direct experience of or a direct knowledge of is the stories of what happens when we're little kids and we're not allowed to speak our native language.
And there are people teaching us not related to us who are using brutal methods to basically indoctrinated and cultureate us into mainstream white English culture.
And this is part of what you're talking about healing that intergenerational wounding that's been there for many generations now.
Yeah. So there's like in my own family alone, there's at least five generations of trauma. And even my own mother wasn't allowed to speak her language.
So it's really important to be doing that work and bringing it back. And I think with this project, even including more youth is just going to further the healing and connect all of them.
Yeah. And of course, your mother is one of the three women leading the three sisters sovereignty project, right? So this is just a tremendous story.
And it's one I hope many of our why on earth network will get involved in and engaged in and support.

And I'll just throw out that you can check out information on three sisters by going to three sisters project.org. And there is a go fund me underway to help support the efforts in the coming year of putting in gardens, of putting in an educational long house, of getting some sustainable micro enterprises launched in underway.
So three sisters project.org is a great place to plug in and to support what's happening here with meadow and her mother Tiffany and the other women and men who are helping to make this happen.
So yeah, definitely excited for folks to have an opportunity to see that and to become a part of that.

And of course, I some folks know that my great grandmother was Mohawk and that that you know, I'm one of the people out there who's got that as part of my heritage, but was totally obviously cut off culturally.
And for me, I get excited thinking I have an opportunity to learn the language a little bit. And it's not easy. It's a beautiful language. I love hearing it. And it's not an easy one for me to learn.
But Dehunjio's, your name has a beautiful, beautiful meaning. Can you can you share with the audience what it means and what it means to you as you're moving here and doing this work here?
So my name, Dehunjio's stuff means she makes the line beautiful. And I was named by my grandmother. It's really kind of astonishing to see how it's manifested and how it's really become my true name.
And I just feeling the connection to the land here has only furthered that.

And you with with your mother and several other women had an amazing ceremony a few days ago, moon lodge ceremony. And I understand that was for you the first lodge ceremony you've had back here on the ancestral homelands. Is that right?

Yeah, so our first our moon ceremony was for all the women. And it was mainly to connect us back to this land because we've been gone for so long. And because we were pushed to our reservations and we haven't been here. And we all really felt that connection while we were in there doing the ceremony.

That's absolutely beautiful. Well, I think another aspect of what's happening that's really important for all of our audience and really all of our society to understand where broadly is that coming out of the Mohawk tradition is a very powerful important special way of relating to each other and relating to the world, the earth. And it's the great law.
And I know that Ben Franklin spent a lot of time among the Mohawk people and that was a big part of some of the most virtuous aspects of what got framed in the Constitution.
And I'm just wondering share with us the great law and how does that play out in what you're doing here.
So it's really hard for us to even follow the great law at home because the pollution has like poisoned our minds and all you can ever be is negative.

And one of the main things we need to have is going to go near and that's a good mind. So coming here has really helped us reconnect with those teachings and really continuing to use it and show our youth how to use it because everyone is just disconnected mainly at home.
And I know the great law has three main tenets, right? We share what those are.
Peace. This is a good mind.
And love.
We've got mom off camera. Yeah.
Yeah.
It's been a while since I've studied that.
So we learn, we basically learn that when we're little children and a lot of because there's no reservation schools other than the freedom school.
And that's in one of the most polluted places.
Oh my gosh.
Our only option is to go to the white school. I mean it's still the majority of us have to go there.
So it's now it's 85%.
So once we, after we're children, if we're not able to go to long house because we can't miss school or the school gives us a hard time for ceremonies.
So after we've all like forgotten basically and it's really hard to relearn things that you knew since you were baby.
Yeah.
That's mainly what we're all doing.
Yeah. It's so beautiful to see you.
And just earlier today, you were doing a bit of this nearby, right?
There's an Irkoy Indian Museum nearby near house cave in Central New York.
And you were over there teaching how many kids were over there?
There was 70.
Yeah.
About 70.
And so we were visiting yesterday that some of the artifacts are just beautiful to look at, right?
And just amazing to be surrounded by all of that.
What were you teaching the kids today? What was going on?
So I was telling this big group about the story of the Cornhouse-style, the No Face-Daw.
Yeah.
And then we helped them to all make them.
And it was so crazy to see all these non-native kids be so accepting.
And they were all amazed that I was there because a lot of people think that the mohaks have died out.
Right.
And even just all Native Americans, they were all like, I thought they all died.
And it was kind of crazy to see that.
And I was speaking to them in the language and they were all so excited and thrilled to be there.
So it was a really good experience.
That's absolutely beautiful.
That's so beautiful.
Yeah. And it sounds like there will be opportunities for a lot more events and gatherings at that museum.
It's a beautiful building, right?
Yeah.
So they want me to volunteer there now.
So I'm going to be there often, me and my mom.
And they want me to do some of the stories and tell them to the groups of kids for school.
So they can learn and know that we're still here.
Yeah, absolutely.
And how.
Yeah.
Well, let's talk a little about sports for a minute.
You also are a lacrosse player, huh?
Yeah.
Retired lacrosse player.
Retired lacrosse player, yeah.
So tell us lacrosse has a very special place in the mohak culture.
Why is that special?
What's that all about?
And what changed recently with the clan mothers around?
Um, so it's originally a medicine game.
It was played by the men.
And we used wooden sticks and it was made like, so like, we don't even have record because it's all oral storytelling.
And, um, so the I grew up on.
It wasn't my mom that ever wanted me to play because the women aren't supposed to play.
We're in our culture.
We're too powerful.
And we're too, um, yeah, like we have too much power over it.
So we can't use it as the medicine.
So, um, my father was the one who got me into playing when I was in third grade.
And even then it was a really controversial thing in our community.
And a lot of people from the long house and the clan mothers and the leaders didn't support it.
So in the last couple of years we've gotten, um, the Bear Clan Mother Louise Herndt.
We got her on board with that.
And we actually have a documentary about the whole process.
It's called Keepers of the Game on Netflix.
Yeah, I, uh, I watch it not well.
I guess one or two years ago and it was awesome, awesome story.
Keepers of the Game.
Um, I'll put that in the show notes to, uh, I'll try to link it for everybody so that it's easy to check that out.
So, uh, do you think you'll end up teaching some others to play some lacrosse down the road?
Yeah, probably.
Um, I mean, we have, uh, I have, uh, on my youth board for three sister sovereignty project.
Um, we have a lot of lacrosse players and they, um, they know how to do the traditional wooden sticks and how to do everything involved with that.
So, um, usually we split so the young men teach the young women and the young women teach the young women.
Yeah, because it is different because, um, we use it more, the women use it more as a sport now.
And it's not really the medicine aspect, but the young men still use that.
So, um, there's more of a spiritual aspect to that too.
And a lot of, like, probably the majority of young men on the reservation play and they've played their whole lives.
Hmm, cool.
I'm wondering too if we might share a little about, uh, the ego feather and, uh, another something very special hanging behind it here.
Yeah.
Uh, this is something from a man who's done a lot to reestablish the presence of the Mohawk people in this region as well, right?
Yeah.
And, uh, could you tell us a little about him and what this is and we'll, we can read it maybe for the audience, right?
Yeah. Um, so Tom Porter, he, well, he's kind of a celebrity back home.
Um, he's really done a lot of work for us in our community and really helped to establish another community,
almost like our three sisters sovereignty project.
So, he was kind of the, um, paved the way for us to even be here and be started.
And, um, he's done a lot of work, a lot of speeches, a lot of top telling our stories and getting the message out there.
There's a lot on YouTube, we used to watch it for our classes even in school.
